## 2. Web App Manifest

The `manifest.json` (or `manifest.webmanifest`) is your app's identity card for the OS. It tells the browser how to display your app when installed.

### Required Properties

```json
{
  "name": "My Application",
  "short_name": "MyApp",
  "description": "A brief, compelling description of the app.",
  "start_url": "/",
  "display": "standalone",
  "background_color": "#1a1a2e",
  "theme_color": "#16213e",
  "orientation": "portrait-primary",
  "scope": "/",
  "icons": [
    { "src": "/icons/icon-192.png", "sizes": "192x192", "type": "image/png" },
    { "src": "/icons/icon-512.png", "sizes": "512x512", "type": "image/png" },
    { "src": "/icons/icon-512-maskable.png", "sizes": "512x512", "type": "image/png", "purpose": "maskable" }
  ]
}
```

### Key Manifest Guidelines

| Property | Best Practice |
|:---|:---|
| `name` | Full app name (max ~45 characters) |
| `short_name` | Truncated name for tight spaces (< 12 characters ideally) |
| `display` | Use `standalone` for native-like look (hides browser chrome). `fullscreen` for immersive apps. Never `browser`. |
| `display_override` | Optional: allows specifying a preference chain, e.g. `["window-controls-overlay", "standalone"]` |
| `background_color` | Must match your app's initial load background to prevent a "white flash" during startup |
| `theme_color` | Colors the browser's status bar / title bar. Should harmonize with your design. |
| `start_url` | URL that opens when the app launches. Often `"/"` or `"/?source=pwa"` for analytics tracking. |
| `scope` | Defines the URL space the PWA controls. URLs outside scope open in the browser. |
| `orientation` | `portrait-primary` for most apps; `any` for apps that benefit from landscape |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The `display: standalone` mode removes the browser's back button. Your app **must** provide its own internal navigation to prevent users from getting stuck.

