## 3. Service Workers

The service worker is the heart of a PWA — a JavaScript file that runs in the background, intercepting network requests, managing caches, and enabling offline functionality.

### Lifecycle

```mermaid
graph LR
    A[Register] --> B[Install]
    B --> C[Activate]
    C --> D[Idle / Controlling]
    D -->|Network Request| E[Fetch Event]
    D -->|New SW Found| F[Waiting]
    F -->|skipWaiting| C
```

### Caching Strategies

Choose the right strategy for each resource type:

| Strategy | When to Use | Behavior |
|:---|:---|:---|
| **Cache First** | Static assets (CSS, JS, fonts, images) | Serves from cache; falls back to network. Fastest. |
| **Network First** | Dynamic API data, user-specific content | Tries network; falls back to cache if offline. Freshest. |
| **Stale-While-Revalidate** | Content that changes occasionally (blog posts, product listings) | Serves cached instantly; fetches update in background. Balanced. |
| **Network Only** | Real-time data (chat, live prices) | Always goes to network. No caching. |
| **Cache Only** | Precached app shell | Only checks cache. Used for core UI skeleton. |

### The App Shell Pattern

The most important architectural pattern for PWAs:

1. **Precache** the minimal HTML, CSS, and JS needed to render the app's UI skeleton (header, nav, layout) during the service worker's `install` event
2. **Serve the shell instantly** from cache on every visit
3. **Fetch dynamic content** (data) separately and inject it into the shell
4. Result: Users see a functional interface immediately, even offline

> [!TIP]
> Use **Workbox** (by Google) instead of writing raw service worker code. It provides production-ready modules for routing (`workbox-routing`), strategies (`workbox-strategies`), precaching (`workbox-precaching`), and cache expiration (`workbox-expiration`).

