## 6. iOS-Specific Guidelines & Workarounds

iOS is more restrictive. Understanding and working around these limitations is **critical** for a quality experience.

### Key Limitations (as of iOS 26, mid-2026)

| Limitation | Impact | Workaround |
|:---|:---|:---|
| **No install prompt** | Users must manually "Add to Home Screen" via Safari's Share menu | Build a custom onboarding banner that teaches users the process |
| **Cache volatility** | Safari may clear PWA data after 7 days of inactivity | Use IndexedDB over localStorage; implement server-side session persistence |
| **No Background Sync** | The Background Sync API is not supported | Listen for the `online` event and trigger sync manually |
| **Limited background execution** | Service workers are killed aggressively when the app is backgrounded | Design for graceful reconnection; avoid relying on long-running SW tasks |
| **No `theme_color` on iOS 26+** | The `theme-color` meta tag / manifest member no longer controls status bar color | Use `<body>` background color or a `position: fixed` header with `backdrop-filter: blur()` |

### Required Apple Meta Tags

```html
<!-- Enable standalone PWA mode on iOS -->
<meta name="apple-mobile-web-app-capable" content="yes">

<!-- Status bar style: default | black | black-translucent -->
<meta name="apple-mobile-web-app-status-bar-style" content="black-translucent">

<!-- App name displayed under the icon -->
<meta name="apple-mobile-web-app-title" content="My App">

<!-- Edge-to-edge rendering -->
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0, viewport-fit=cover">

<!-- Touch icon (180×180) -->
<link rel="apple-touch-icon" href="/icons/apple-touch-icon.png">
```

### CSS Safe Areas (Notch & Home Bar)

When using `viewport-fit=cover`, content extends behind the notch and home indicator. Protect it:

```css
:root {
  --sat: env(safe-area-inset-top);
  --sab: env(safe-area-inset-bottom);
  --sal: env(safe-area-inset-left);
  --sar: env(safe-area-inset-right);
}

body {
  padding-top: var(--sat);
  padding-bottom: var(--sab);
  padding-left: var(--sal);
  padding-right: var(--sar);
}

/* Or apply to specific elements */
.app-header {
  padding-top: calc(1rem + var(--sat));
}

.bottom-nav {
  padding-bottom: calc(0.5rem + var(--sab));
}
```

### iOS Install Prompt — Custom Onboarding

Since iOS has no native install prompt, build your own:

1. **Detect iOS + Safari** using user agent or `navigator.standalone === false`
2. **Show a contextual banner** after the user has engaged (not on first visit)
3. **Visually guide** the user: show an animated arrow pointing to the Share button, then "Add to Home Screen"
4. **Persist dismissal** so the banner doesn't annoy returning users
5. **Don't show on non-Safari iOS browsers** (they can't install PWAs)

