## 10. App Update Strategy

### The Problem

When you deploy new code, users may still be running the old version because:
1. The old service worker is still controlling the page
2. Assets are served from cache

### Recommended Update Flow

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant Browser
    participant OldSW as Old Service Worker
    participant NewSW as New Service Worker
    participant UI as User Interface

    Browser->>NewSW: Detects new SW file (byte diff)
    NewSW->>NewSW: Installs (precaches new assets)
    NewSW->>NewSW: Enters "waiting" state
    NewSW-->>UI: Triggers "waiting" event
    UI->>UI: Shows "Update Available" toast
    Note right of UI: User clicks "Update Now"
    UI->>NewSW: postMessage({ type: 'SKIP_WAITING' })
    NewSW->>NewSW: self.skipWaiting()
    NewSW->>Browser: Takes control
    Browser->>UI: controllerchange event
    UI->>UI: window.location.reload()
```

### Best Practices

| Practice | Rationale |
|:---|:---|
| **Show a non-intrusive toast/banner** | Don't force-refresh — users may be mid-task |
| **Give users control** | "Update available — Refresh to update" with a button |
| **Never cache `service-worker.js` aggressively** | Serve with `Cache-Control: no-cache` so browsers detect updates |
| **Version your caches** | Name caches with a version string; purge old caches in `activate` event |
| **Use Workbox `workbox-window`** | Handles the `waiting` event detection and `skipWaiting` messaging automatically |

