## 13. Accessibility

A PWA must meet **WCAG 2.1 Level AA** standards. Accessibility is not optional — it's a quality requirement.

### Key Requirements

| Area | Guidelines |
|:---|:---|
| **Keyboard Navigation** | All functionality accessible via keyboard. Logical tab order. Visible focus indicators. No keyboard traps. |
| **Screen Readers** | Semantic HTML (`<nav>`, `<main>`, `<button>`, `<h1>`–`<h6>`). Proper `aria-label` on custom elements. Logical reading order. |
| **Touch Targets** | Minimum 44×44px (Apple) / 48×48dp (Material Design) |
| **Color Contrast** | 4.5:1 for normal text, 3:1 for large text |
| **Motion** | Respect `prefers-reduced-motion`. Provide controls to pause animations. |
| **Responsive Reflow** | Content must work at 320px width without horizontal scrolling |
| **System Settings** | Respect OS-level text scaling and dark mode preferences |

### Testing Strategy

| Method | Coverage | Tools |
|:---|:---|:---|
| **Automated Scanning** | 30–40% of issues | Lighthouse, axe-core, WAVE |
| **Manual Keyboard Testing** | Focus order, traps, missing indicators | Tab, Shift+Tab, Enter, Escape, Arrow keys |
| **Screen Reader Testing** | Full assistive tech experience | VoiceOver (iOS/Mac), TalkBack (Android), NVDA (Windows) |
| **Zoom Testing** | Reflow at 200% zoom | Browser zoom, OS text scaling |

