## 16. Key Takeaways

### The Golden Rules

1. **Design for iOS first, then enhance for Android.** iOS has the strictest limitations. If it works well on iOS, it will work excellently on Android.

2. **The app shell is non-negotiable.** Precache your UI skeleton so it loads instantly. This single pattern makes the biggest difference in perceived quality.

3. **Offline is a feature, not an error state.** Design graceful offline experiences — informative fallback pages, cached content, and pending state indicators.

4. **The install prompt is a conversation, not a command.** On Android, time it contextually. On iOS, teach users with a friendly onboarding flow.

5. **Performance IS the experience.** A 3-second load time and janky scrolling will negate every other effort. Optimize relentlessly for Core Web Vitals.

6. **Touch targets and safe areas are dealbreakers.** A 30px button that gets clipped by the notch will instantly betray the app as a web wrapper.

7. **Updates must be graceful.** Never force-refresh. Show a polite "Update available" toast and let the user choose when to apply.

8. **Accessibility is quality.** Semantic HTML, keyboard navigation, and screen reader support are not "nice to haves" — they define whether your app is truly production-grade.

9. **Security is foundational.** HTTPS, strict CSP, scoped service workers, and no sensitive data in caches. These are non-negotiable.

10. **Test on real devices.** Simulators miss real-world PWA behaviors. Always test installation, offline mode, and push notifications on physical Android and iOS devices.

